The Yobe State COVID-19 Prevention and Control Committee under the leadership of the deputy governor, Idi Barde Gubana, has approved the extension of the stay-at-home and work-from-home directive for civil servants below Grade Level 12. In a press release signed by the commissioner for Home Affairs, Information and Culture, Mallam Abdullahi Bego, he said that the committee resolved that in view of the ongoing prevalence of COVID-19 in certain parts of the country, movement in and out of the state, especially across its borders with Jigawa and Bauchi States, will remain restricted till further notice. Bego said that the committee on Tuesday reviewed the prevention and preparedness measures which have been put in place to prevent an outbreak of the coronavirus disease across the state. He said: “All these are measures that cut across sectors and domains and that are designed to ensure a holistic and comprehensive approach to protecting the people and maintaining the zero-case status of the state. The committee remains profoundly grateful to the people of the state for their cooperation and adherence to the guidelines on social distancing, regular hand washing, stay-at-home, good respiratory etiquette, and other measures that have been recommended as effective in preventing a COVID-19 infection. “However, the committee also resolves as follows: That in view of the ongoing prevalence of COVID-19 in certain parts of the country, movement in and out of the state, especially across our borders with Bauchi and Jigawa States, will remain restricted,” he said. Bego stated that the police, civil defence and vigilantes will continue to enforce the restriction, adding that the stay-at-home and work-from-home directive for civil servants from Grade Level 12 and below had been extended till April 30, 2020. 